= Facts are the foundation of democracy and journalism. Who maintains them when Big Tech pulls back? =

{{info}}
**Author:** Robert Schaub (Founder and Lead Developer, FactHarbor.ch) **Date:** 1 April 2026
**Published on:** [[LinkedIn>>https://www.linkedin.com/feed/update/urn:li:activity:7445085142844456960/]]
**Deutsche Version:** [[LinkedIn April 2026 DE>>FactHarbor.Organisation.Partner & User Relations.Presentations.LinkedIn April 2026 DE.WebHome]]
{{/info}}

Some people believe bold claims with little evidence. Others step back entirely: //"I don't read the news anymore. I can't trust anything."//

Both reactions are understandable. When reasoning is hidden, and sources lack transparency, trust erodes. And the infrastructure that was supposed to help is shrinking — **Meta exited** the Third-Party Fact-Checking Program, **Google reduced** ClaimReview visibility, and fact-checking organizations **lost significant platform funding**.

The problem isn't that people don't care about truth — it's that the **structure behind information is invisible**.

That's why I've been building **FactHarbor** — full-time, since November 2025.

----

FactHarbor is an **open-source tool for automated fact-checking**. Submit any claim or article — the system extracts verifiable statements, searches supporting and opposing evidence across the web and academic databases, scores every source for credibility, and runs a **structured AI debate** where different providers argue for and against each claim.

**This is not just asking ChatGPT a question.**
AI follows tightly prescribed workflows and structured data contracts. **Only evidence-backed objections can change a verdict.** Every conclusion links to cited evidence — so you can **inspect the reasoning and judge for yourself**.

The result is not a single label, but a **multi-perspective evidence landscape** showing where a claim is well-supported, where it's contradicted, and where reasonable people may still disagree.

